│ The `llvm.fshl` intrinsic performs a funnel shift left operation, which concatenates two values,       │
│ shifts the combined value left, and extracts the most significant bits to produce a result of the same │
│ size as the original arguments. This operation is sensitive to the relationship between its operands,  │
│ and any transformation that modifies these operands independently can lead to incorrect behavior or    │
│ the introduction of poison values.                                                                     │
│                                                                                                        │
│ The bug in the `SimplifyDemandedUseBits` function arises because it simplifies the operands of the     │
│ `llvm.fshl` intrinsic independently, without considering their interdependence. This can lead to       │
│ transformations that violate the intrinsic's semantics, as demonstrated in the provided reproducer.    │
│                                                                                                        │
│ To address this issue, I will add a special case for the `llvm.fshl` intrinsic in the                  │
│ `SimplifyDemandedUseBits` function. This case will ensure that the operands are not simplified         │
│ independently and that any transformation preserves the semantics of the `llvm.fshl` intrinsic.        │
│                                                                                                        │
│ Let me first retrieve the implementation of the `SimplifyDemandedUseBits` function to identify the     │
│ exact location where the fix should be applied.                                                        │
